Haftner is the founder and previous director of Street Meet: Saskatoon’s Annual Street, Graffiti and Public Art Festival. She has exhibited work nationally and internationally, and is one of seven public artists commissioned to create a public work for Saskatoon’s 2013 Placemaker Program. Haftner is currently pursuing her Master of Fine Arts at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago. Her 3D printing practice involves using waste plastic to create homemade filament for use with FDM printers.

The Enable Community Foundation advances and extends e-NABLE, a fast-growing global network of digital humanitarians using technology to design, fabricate, and disseminate free prosthetic-like hand and arm to those who ​need them.

The Enable Community Foundation aims to implement and validate a scalable high-tech infrastructure that matches recipients with volunteers who create open-sourced assistive technologies…for free or minimal costs. It supports educational materials and program to recruit and develop more digital humanitarians. And it is developing partnerships and programs to bring these inspirational new methods and solutions to the entire world.

In the long run, crowd-sourced digital humanitarians can address many kinds of unmet needs. In the near term, we are “changing the world, one hand at a time.”

3d Printing hobbyist since April 2015. Almost attaining a successfully modified printer without the need to always keep a close eye on it.

Heavily modified Prusa i3

  1. Replaced metal printbed on blue tape with Glass printbed coated with hairspray (works well with both ABS and PLA and greatly prevents warping)
  2. Replaced spool holder with sliding door rollers to reduce resistance of spool filament against extruder
  3. Replaced direct extruder design with bowden extruder design for lighter x carriage and more consistent filament feeding.
  4. Replaced hotend with e3dv6 clone, greatly reduces filament nozzle jams and better cooling to prevent heat creep.
  5. Added fans to stepper motors to prevent overheating and warping of printer parts. (namely X carriage and X motorend carriage)
  6. Stopped printing by usb-stream from computer due to constant EMI inteference. Now printing using microsd card eliminates machine from stopping mid print.
  7. Purchased better slicing software simplify3d, because i suck at configuring slic3r.

Hi,

My name is Ivan and I was introduced to 3-D printing in university but now I get to do it at work. I realized how effective 3-D printing could be for prototyping projects versus having to go to the machine shop and machine material there. The machine shop without a doubt has its place but for my prototyping I think 3-D printing will be the way to go.

My background is in Engineering Physics and Mechanical Engineering but I seem to be called upon to do more embedded systems and electronics prototyping. Currently, I am involved with accessibility, bio-electronics and applied physics research in the British Columbia area.

If anyone is interested in collaborating on projects or just bouncing off ideas I am all ears!

Cheers!
